Expensive but worth it. The dude behind the bar was nice too. I came in when the place was getting ready to close and he still let me grab some food and a drink and we just kind of talked about life and stuff. In reality, it’s closer to a 4.5, but let me share our experience! We made reservations for the day before Valentine’s. We were greeted at the door and then they took our coats for us and sat us in a semi-private area. Our waiter, Peter, was with us shortly and was so enthusiastic. He made you feel like somehow you were taking a journey with the food, which we loved. He was not pushy to hurry us at all, but never made us feel like we were waiting for him. We started our meal with the smoked pork belly appetizer which was delightful. We followed that up with seafood bisque and a wedge salad. Let me tell you—my favorite blue cheese dressing ever! Not too strong, very smooth. The croutons were clearly house-made and very good as well. Then, my husband and I both ordered the ribeye with the upgraded whipped potatoes baked with cheese. So worth the upgrade! (Side note—the menu says no substitutes, but you can sub sides. However, they up-charge these things, which is to be expected at a place like this, but it’s worth mentioning.) One of us had the asparagus and one the mushrooms as our other sides. Both good choices. The steaks were good—but honestly, not a $49 steak. It was tender and very marbled, but it lacked a little in the flavor department. It was cooked to order quite well though. Not over- or under-done. The wine sauce was good, but also not super flavorful or abundant. We finished off with a couple of desserts. Apparently the oatmeal pie with cinnamon gelato is the most popular thing there, so we got that and a chocolate cheesecake. Honestly, these were the least impressive parts. The oatmeal pie was sweet and was fine, but not to mine or hubby’s taste really. The chocolate cheesecake was smooth and also fine, but it wasn’t very chocolatey, and it was clear that the berries came from being frozen—at least that’s how it looked. It seems like a place like this with such high quality food should at least have fresh berries with the cheesecake, not frozen. Call me picky! Anyhow, our overall experience was good and we’ll probably go again. If you plan to experience Joseph’s, make sure you are prepared to pay! The steaks are not priced as they are sold at market value which continually changes. By the time we tipped, the bill was about $200 for 2 of us.
Food was to pricey for both the taste, lacking flavor, and portion size. Not a good amount of things to choose from on menu.

DINNER REVIEW  One of the best meals as a family we've had in a long time. We came here to celebrate my sister's graduation from the University of Iowa and luckily we had a reservation (they were also asking for credit cards to hold reservations given how highly-desired this place was for graduation night).  SETTING: Classic steakhouse vibes with a dimly-lit bar, tall/soft chairs, and several people beyond the main waiters running around filling waters and clearing tables. That's what makes me think of a nicer steakhouse.  FOOD: What I love about Joseph's is that you can get high-quality steakhouse food and service at a reasonable price, especially compared to where I'm used to going in Chicago and Boston. The 16 oz. ribeye I ordered was $36 and it could easily have been $60 in the cities I just mentioned.  Our steaks came with a soup or salad so I started with the seafood bisque which was warm and creamy and very flavorful. Can't remember many seafood bisques I've had to compare it to but I liked this soup.  Then came the main event, the ribeye steak. I don't often cook red meat for myself at home so this was a nice treat. It was a boneless ribeye that was cooked to a perfect medium rare and covered in a red wine demi glace. We paired it with the Boursin Whipped potatoes (a MUST GET), the Brussels sprouts and bacon (think shaved Brussels sprouts), and the mushrooms (small mushrooms, not sliced). We got the large versions of each of the sides which were, again, very reasonably priced but they weren't too big. It was perfect for my family of four but if you had more people, I would definitely get two orders of the Boursin Whipped potatoes.  We were too full for a big dessert but my sister really wanted creme brûlée so we got dish of it (only $3!). We all tried a bit and it was some of the best I've had.  If you are in Iowa City and looking for one of the nicest dinners in town, look no further than Joseph's.

My husband took me here for my birthday and it was AMAZING! The service was fantastic, and out waiter was top notch! My only complaint is that the table of younger men next to us was extremely loud in an otherwise quiet ambience and the minute we sat next to them, I heard them LOUDLY discussing and laughing about how a young child was murdered (in detail) in some movie they were talking about. As a mother of 4, (and 1 stillborn) this was an awful conversation to hear (especially when they are so loud that you can't ignore them) on your birthday. I didn't want to be "that person" so I did my best to block their noise out. Aside from that, great great GREAT food and service.

What a disappointment! With the reviews of this place (and the prices), I was expecting a big-city fine dining experience. They weren't busy; we got there right when they opened & were the only people there, so there's no excuse for our experience:  I had the seafood bisque, which was underseasoned & too acidic. (I added butter & salt, which made it better.) My scallop meal was OVERseasoned, with only 3 scallops. My potato risotto was so raw that it crunched.  To add insult to injury, the prices on the bill were slightly higher than those on the menu--the martini was $2 more, and so were my scallops. If it had been a $35 meal instead of a $75 meal (actually, my husband only had an appetizer), I wouldn't be mad, but at these prices, we won't be going back.

Joseph's remains one of the better places to eat in Iowa City. I believe it's an institution to that restaurant community.  Other steakhouses nearby, like the Iowa Chophouse, have fluctuated in quality, in my opinion.  Whenever we chose to celebrate a with a nice meal and a glass of wine, Joseph's prepared my rare 8oz filet mignon right. I've found some places over salt the steak, over cook rare cuts, or lose the steaks own flavor with copious amounts of strongly flavored sauces and toppings.  I've been happy with Joseph's these past 8 years.

Everyone else I ate with seemed to thouroughly enjoy their food and I plan to come here every once in a while. The price of everything is quite high and the entrance is somewhat unappealing, but everything else this restaurant has completely overshadows the negatives.  TL;DR: amazing atmosphere, simplicity, food, and service, but expensive.

If you want class and delicious food at a similar price point I would strongly encourage you to look into Orchard Green, an absolute gem, not only of Iowa City but restaurants in the midwest.

Our family of four went to celebrate our college son's birthday as it seemed to be one of the few places in IC where we could get seafood. The decor is weirdly fancy with curtained off areas for tables. The server was very friendly and helpful although the main issue we had (the pricing) was not something she could help us with. Entrees are all over $25 and most are at least $5 or $6 more than that. Very little is included with the entree although my steak did come with a generous, but uninteresting salad. Sides began at $6. My son ordered the sea bass and much to our dismay, immediately after ordering it, we overheard the party at the next table complaining about that same dish! He dismissed them as he is an adventurous eater, but found the meal not to his liking either as it was smothered in an ill-chosen Amaretto sauce. My husband's halibut (the special) was edible, but also overpriced. My own choice, a ribeye, rang in at $31 and was no better than one I have made at home for much less money (and I am no great cook.) My husband and son did enjoy the lobster bisque, but that was the highlight. The rest was just nothing special and certainly did not warrant the high pricing in a college town. My younger son was not feeling great so just had fries and pronounced them to be delicious. So, hey! The fries are good! We wish we had checked an online menu beforehand so we would have known what we were getting into. No bang for your buck at this place!
A nice classy restaurant in Iowa City. We had very nice meals most of the time. The service is excellent. The tables for two are big for two people. It is pricy, but good service.
